Consciousness is defined in biopsychology as the subjective experience of the self and the external environment, which includes perceptions, thoughts, emotions, and intentions. It refers to being aware of one's surroundings, oneself, and one's own mental moods. The exploration of the precise brain activity and neural processes linked with conscious experience is referred to as studying the "neural correlates" of consciousness. This might entail determining which brain areas and neural circuits are active during various conscious states and investigating how these neural processes give birth to the subjective experience of consciousness. Experimental approaches for studying consciousness include neuroimaging, neuropsychology, and electrophysiology. Researchers may use these approaches to investigate the neural activity and brain areas linked with various conscious states such as perception, attention, and memory. The use of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to research the neural correlates of visual awareness is an example of a study on the brain processes involved in consciousness. This research might entail showing individuals visual stimuli such as pictures or patterns while utilizing fMRI to measure their brain activity. The brain activity of people who are aware of visual stimuli and those who are not might then be compared in order to discover the exact brain areas and neural circuits related with visual awareness. Tsuchiya and Koch employed a similar strategy to examine the brain underpinnings of visual awareness in a 2006 research. They utilized an fMRI to assess individuals' brain activity while they watched a quick stream of pictures, and discovered that when people reported being aware of the visuals, a particular brain area called the primary visual cortex (V1) was more active. This work supports the involvement of V1 in visual awareness and illustrates how fMRI may be utilized to investigate the neural correlates of consciousness. 